\section{Imports}

The shell backend stays in the standard library.  That keeps the first
release easy to install and focuses the implementation effort on the PTY
behaviour itself rather than on a higher-level UI framework.

We also keep editor launching in the same module because it has the same
terminal constraint as the interactive shell path: the child process must
talk directly to the user's TTY rather than to a captured pipe.

That shared constraint makes the editor path a useful contrast before we
build the heavier PTY machinery.  The editor case shows what direct TTY
ownership looks like when we do 
not need to capture an interactive transcript.

