\section{Creating shell timestamps}

The shell module keeps its own UTC helper so it can be used without
depending on the state layer.

<<functions>>=
def utc_now() -> str:
    """Return the current time as an ISO 8601 UTC string."""

    return datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()
@


\section{Preparing the shell environment}

We keep the prompt explicit so the transcript reads like a shell session
when shown in the review command.  Nested tutorials should also expose
their own names in the prompt, otherwise the inner shell is hard to tell
apart from the outer one.

Resetting [[PROMPT_COMMAND]] avoids host-specific shell hooks from
polluting the transcript.

<<functions>>=
def build_shell_environment(
    extra_env: dict[str, str] | None = None,
    *,
    prompt_name: str = "tutorial",
) -> dict[str, str]:
    """Return the environment used for tutorial shell sessions."""

    env = dict(os.environ)
    if extra_env:
        env.update(extra_env)
    env["PS1"] = f"{prompt_name} $ "
    env["PROMPT_COMMAND"] = ""
    env["TERM"] = env.get("TERM", "xterm-256color")
    return env
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_build_shell_environment_sets_prompt():
    env = build_shell_environment(
        {"EXTRA": "yes"},
        prompt_name="using-tutorials",
    )

    assert env["PS1"] == "using-tutorials $ "
    assert env["EXTRA"] == "yes"
