\section{Resolving which editor to run}

[[EDITOR]] often contains both a program name and flags such as
[[code --wait]] or [[emacsclient -c]].  Splitting that value with
[[shlex]] preserves the conventional shell-style configuration while
still letting us append the target file path as a separate argument.

When [[EDITOR]] is not set, we fall back to a short list of common
interactive editors and pick the first one available on [[PATH]].

<<constants>>=
DEFAULT_EDITORS = ("vim", "vi", "nano")
@

<<functions>>=
def resolve_editor_command(
    env: dict[str, str] | None = None,
) -> tuple[str, ...]:
    """Return the configured editor command as an argument tuple."""

    environment = os.environ if env is None else env
    editor = environment.get("EDITOR", "").strip()
    if editor:
        return tuple(shlex.split(editor))

    for candidate in DEFAULT_EDITORS:
        resolved = shutil.which(candidate)
        if resolved:
            return (resolved,)

    raise RuntimeError(
        "No editor configured. Set $EDITOR or install vim, vi, or nano."
    )
@

Let's verify that an explicit [[EDITOR]] value wins and that the fallback
search returns the first available common editor.

<<test functions>>=
def test_resolve_editor_command_uses_editor_environment_variable():
    assert resolve_editor_command({"EDITOR": "code --wait"}) == (
        "code",
        "--wait",
    )


def test_resolve_editor_command_falls_back_to_first_available_editor(monkeypatch):
    monkeypatch.delenv("EDITOR", raising=False)
    monkeypatch.setattr(
        shutil,
        "which",
        lambda name: f"/usr/bin/{name}" if name == "vi" else None,
    )

    assert resolve_editor_command() == ("/usr/bin/vi",)
