\section{Running interactive editor sessions}

Unlike the PTY-backed shell, an interactive editor should own the user's
terminal directly.  Full-screen programs such as [[vim]] already know how
to manage the terminal when connected to the inherited TTY, and we do not
need to capture every keystroke.  We therefore launch the editor as a
foreground subprocess, wait for it to exit, and then read the file.

This is the simpler of the two interaction paths in the module.  Once we
have seen the direct-TTY case, the remaining sections can focus on what the
shell path adds beyond it: claiming a PTY as the controlling terminal,
relaying bytes, and preserving a faithful transcript.

