\section{Claiming the PTY as a controlling terminal}

Attaching bash to the slave side of a PTY is not quite enough for a real
interactive shell.  Bash also expects that terminal to be its controlling
terminal, otherwise it disables job control and prints warnings before the
prompt appears.

This is where the chapter returns to its main PTY story.  The editor path
needed only direct access to the user's TTY; the shell path must also make
the PTY behave like a real login terminal for bash.

Python 3.10 does not yet offer [[os.login_tty()]], so the smallest fix is
to do the setup just before [[exec]] in the child process.  We start a new
session and claim file descriptor [[0]], which already points at the PTY
slave by then.

<<functions>>=
def prepare_child_terminal() -> None:
    """Turn the PTY slave on fd ``0`` into the controlling terminal."""

    os.setsid()
    if hasattr(termios, "TIOCSCTTY"):
        fcntl.ioctl(0, termios.TIOCSCTTY, 0)
@


\section{Launching bash on a configured PTY}

The scripted and interactive shells must start bash in exactly the same PTY
configuration.  A shared helper keeps the controlling-terminal fix in one
place and ensures both paths see the same prompt and shell options.

[[pre_command]] adds one extra requirement for shell-backed steps.  From the
student's perspective, they've already run the setup; they do not know each
step spawns a fresh shell; the tutorial should preserve the illusion of one
continuous terminal session; re-showing setup commands each step would expose
the seams.  Bash rcfiles give us exactly that behaviour: setup commands run
before the first prompt appears, so [[cd]], [[export]], or [[source]] affect
the session the learner sees without leaking into the transcript as authored
commands.

We write that setup script to a temporary rcfile because bash already knows
how to source one script before showing the prompt.  The helper keeps two
important invariants in one place: the script ends with a newline so the last
line is sourced normally, and the temporary file is removed afterwards even if
shell startup fails.

<<functions>>=
@contextmanager
def pre_command_rcfile(script: str):
    """Yield a temporary rcfile path containing ``script``."""

    file_handle = tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile(
        mode="w",
        encoding="utf-8",
        suffix=".sh",
        delete=False,
    )
    try:
        text = script if script.endswith("\n") else script + "\n"
        file_handle.write(text)
        file_handle.close()
        yield file_handle.name
    finally:
        try:
            os.unlink(file_handle.name)
        except FileNotFoundError:
            pass
@

<<functions>>=
def spawn_shell_process(
    *,
    workspace: str | Path,
    shell: str = "/bin/bash",
    prompt_name: str = "tutorial",
    env: dict[str, str] | None = None,
    rcfile: str | None = None,
) -> tuple[int, subprocess.Popen]:
    """Start bash on a PTY and return the master fd and child process."""

    workspace_path = Path(workspace)
    master_fd, slave_fd = pty.openpty()
    try:
        argv = [shell, "--noprofile"]
        if rcfile is None:
            argv.append("--norc")
        else:
            argv.extend(["--rcfile", rcfile])
        argv.append("-i")
        process = subprocess.Popen(
            argv,
            cwd=workspace_path,
            env=build_shell_environment(env, prompt_name=prompt_name),
            stdin=slave_fd,
            stdout=slave_fd,
            stderr=slave_fd,
            preexec_fn=prepare_child_terminal,
            close_fds=True,
        )
    except Exception:
        os.close(master_fd)
        os.close(slave_fd)
        raise

    os.close(slave_fd)
    return master_fd, process
@


\section{Treating PTY EOF consistently}

Pseudo-terminals signal end-of-file differently from ordinary files.  Some
systems return an empty byte string, while Linux often raises [[EIO]] once
the slave side disappears.  Treating both cases as EOF keeps the relay and
drain loops from spinning forever after the shell exits.

<<functions>>=
def read_pty_output(master_fd: int) -> bytes | None:
    """Read one PTY chunk, or return ``None`` at end-of-file."""

    try:
        data = os.read(master_fd, 4096)
    except OSError as error:
        if error.errno == errno.EIO:
            return None
        raise

    if not data:
        return None
    return data
@

Let's verify that both common PTY EOF signals are normalised to
[[None]].

<<test functions>>=
def test_read_pty_output_treats_eio_as_eof(monkeypatch):
    def raise_eio(master_fd, size):
        raise OSError(errno.EIO, "Input/output error")

    monkeypatch.setattr(os, "read", raise_eio)

    assert read_pty_output(3) is None


def test_read_pty_output_treats_empty_read_as_eof(monkeypatch):
    monkeypatch.setattr(os, "read", lambda master_fd, size: b"")

    assert read_pty_output(3) is None
@


\section{Reading all output from a PTY}

Both the scripted and interactive variants need the same drain logic:
keep reading from the PTY until the shell exits and no more output is
available.

<<functions>>=
def read_transcript(master_fd: int, process: subprocess.Popen) -> str:
    """Drain PTY output until ``process`` exits and the PTY closes."""

    chunks = bytearray()
    master_open = True
    while True:
        readable, _, _ = select.select(
            [master_fd] if master_open else [],
            [],
            [],
            0.05,
        )
        if master_open and master_fd in readable:
            data = read_pty_output(master_fd)
            if data is None:
                master_open = False
            else:
                chunks.extend(data)
                continue

        if process.poll() is not None and not master_open:
            break

    return chunks.decode("utf-8", errors="replace")
@


